If the relevant criterion is expressed as one where the court is “satisfied” about a certain matter, that criterion tends to be regarded as involving a relevantly subjective assessment and similar to the exercise of true discretion: DAO v R (2011) 278 ALR 765; [2011] NSWCCA 63;  BC201102128 at [29] . Alternatively the criterion may, by its nature, imply a substantially subjective assessment. For example, in proceedings for family provision (eg under the 
Succession Act 2006
), where an applicant must establish that “adequate” provision has not been made for their “proper maintenance … or advancement”, it has been held that appeals against findings on those issues are subject to the same principles that apply to appeals from discretionary decisions: Singer v Berghouse (No 2) (1994) 181 CLR 201 at 212; 68 ALJR 653 at 658; 123 ALR 481;  BC9404642 ; Golosky v Golosky  (NSWCA, Kirby P, Handley and Cripps JJA, CA40012/91, 5 October 1993, unreported, BC9302134) per Kirby P; Walter v De Jong  (NSWSC, Cole, Beazley and Stein A, CA40620/96, 5 September 1997, unreported, BC9704560); Green v Robinson (1995) 36 NSWLR 96 at 112–113; 18 Fam LR 594; (1995) DFC 95-159;  BC9504213 .

